\subsection{2024 National Baccalauréat, Exercise 7 (Probabilistic Recurrence)}
\textbf{Problem Statement:}  
In a lottery‐style game, a player chooses either a red ball or a blue ball each draw, with replacement. Let $p$ be the probability of choosing a red ball on the first draw.  
\begin{itemize}
  \item If the previous draw was red, the probability of choosing red next is $0.8$.
  \item If the previous draw was blue, the probability of choosing blue next is $0.6$.
  \item Let $p_n$ be the probability of choosing a red ball on the $n$th draw.
\end{itemize}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Write the recurrence relation between $p_{n+1}$ and $p_n$.
  \item Use a matrix method to find the general term $p_n$ and its limit.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Solution:}  
The recurrence is
\[
p_{n+1} = 0.8\,p_n + (1 - 0.6)\,(1 - p_n) 
= 0.4\,p_n + 0.4.
\]
Define $\mathbf{y}_n = \begin{pmatrix}p_n \\ 1\end{pmatrix}$. Then
\[
\mathbf{y}_{n+1} 
= \begin{pmatrix}0.4 & 0.4 \\[4pt] 0 & 1\end{pmatrix} 
\mathbf{y}_n, 
\quad \mathbf{y}_1 = \begin{pmatrix}p_1 \\ 1\end{pmatrix}.
\]
Let $A = \begin{pmatrix}0.4 & 0.4 \\ 0 & 1\end{pmatrix}$. Its eigenvalues are $0.4$ and $1$, with eigenvectors $(1,\,0)^T$ and $(1,\,1)^T$ respectively. Expanding $\mathbf{y}_1$ in that basis yields
\[
p_n = \frac{2}{3} + \Bigl(p_1 - \frac{2}{3}\Bigr)\,(0.4)^{\,n-1}, 
\quad \lim_{n\to\infty} p_n = \frac{2}{3}.
\]

